    essay 1

This week's notes.

1 -- 

The fact that humans are social animals is pretty well-known. Thus,
the relationship between success and a person's social ability is
quite strong. Building solid connections with people is one of the
greatest investments due to the fact that we depend on society in
order to achieve success, recognition or status. If we were all alone,
those concepts wouldn't even exist.

It's by acknowledging the hierarchies that are present in society and
winning over people's ego (perhaps even their narcissistic
tendencies?) that you can 'navigate' through waves of people in a more
'confident' manner. This also heavily implies that the meritocracy in
which we live is based on raw, human interaction, contrary to what
modern society sometimes thinks, which is a meritocracy solely built
upon our achievements. We must'nt reject our own humanity in an
industrialized world.

2 --

Software is a completely man-made concept. Due to the fact that we
tend to create coherent systems, we are in a constant push-pull trying
to counter the natural consecuences that software will eventually
encounter.  When it comes to actually developing software, thinking in
a simple manner is key. When things start to get complex, it's often a
sign that the design has started to develop flaws. As developers, we
should be wary of unnecessary complications.

3 --

Creativity is just a small percentage of material success. Persistence
and actually getting stuff done is what'll eventually bear fruit.

4 --

Industrialization has given most of the developed (and developing)
world the most comfortable life we could ever imagine. We branched out
from our hunter-gatherer tribes so much that we've begun to plague
ourselves with thoughts of desire that've only grown as civilization
has managed to progress scientifically and technologically. Thanks to
the fact that we've cast aside our primitive, human roots, we now
pursue the idea of happiness. This has caused us to live a slaves to
our meaningless decisions.

We should try to feel life a bit more from time to time. The point
isn't to pursue happiness but to live as humans were intended to live:
strongly connected to the world and society.

5 --

The shell is sometimes overlooked in today's era of computing but with
some rudimentary shell skills, you're able to automate a lot of tasks
(and do some cool stuff as well!).

6 --

The scientific method has a strong presence inside problem solving in
general. Making good use out of tried and tested methods and tools in
our daily lives will always lead to good results (perhaps not the
right results, but very clear results). If it isn't broken, don't fix
it. This statement sums up the scientific method as it is today pretty
well.

7 --

By coming together, we can see the value of casting away the ego and
see our actions add up to something greater. Knowing that we aren't
alone in this world leads to giving up on the individual and
transcending into the collective universe.

8 --

Tapping into creativity means being able to let the subconscious mind
'breathe' and letting it bond with the conscious mind. We can do this
by expressing ourselves nonstop or by engaging in physical activity,
depending on the type of person you are, one might be better than the
other. Creativity is also often percieved as something that only
happens by once in a lifetime for a group of select people but more
often than not, great creative minds have failed countless times and
actually 'exercise' their creativity persistently to the point that it
becomes a very well practiced skill.

9 --

People tend to resist change and it makes sense why they do it. By
doubting others and challenging our thoughts, we can test out if ideas
are good or not. Sadly, on most occasions we simply dismiss new ideas
quickly without giving them some real consideration. Progress is made
from challenging new ideas and testing out if they're ok or not.

10 --

In order to improve a skill, practicing deliberately (not aimlessly)
and having access to an expert coach is a sure way to achieve mastery.

11 --

Finally, when it comes to teaching someone a skill, you have to keep
two things in mind: not overworking them (this way they have more
'mental energy') and teaching them with extremely clear and small
examples of something that can be reproducible. This way, progress is
built solidly and the student can still have some leftover energy.

